05981nam a22008055i 9780231540537DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20152015nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a2015009579  a(OCoLC)1013953430  a97802315405377 a10.7312/cran174162doi  a(DE-B1597)458292  a(OCoLC)940680058  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY00aB105.A55bB43 2016 4aB105.A55bB43 2016 7aNAT0390002bisacsh04a179/.322300aBeastly Morality :bAnimals as Ethical Agents /ced. by Jonathan K. Crane.  aPilot project,eBook available to selected US libraries only 1aNew York, NY : bColumbia University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource (296 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tOne. Beastly Morality -- tPart One. The Permeability of Morality -- tTwo. De-humanizing Morality -- tThree. HumAnI(m)Morality -- tFour. Not All Dogs Go to Heaven -- tPart Two. Observing Animal Morality -- tFive. Animal Empathy as Moral Building Block -- tSix. Humans, Other Animals, and the Biology of Morality -- tSeven. Moral Mutts -- tEight. Fighting Fair -- tPart Three. Reading Animal Morality -- tNine. Reading, Teaching Insects -- tTen. Jakushin’s Dogs and the Goodness of Animals -- tPart Four. Reconceiving Animal Morality -- tEleven. Just Chimpanzees? -- tTwleve. Brutal Justice? -- tPart Five. Epilogue -- tThirteen. Beastly Morality: Untangling Possibilities -- tList of Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aWe have come to regard nonhuman animals as beings of concern, and we even grant them some legal protections. But until we understand animals as moral agents in and of themselves, they will be nothing more than distant recipients of our largesse. Featuring original essays by philosophers, ethicists, religionists, and ethologists, including Marc Bekoff, Frans de Waal, and Elisabetta Palagi, this collection demonstrates the ability of animals to operate morally, process ideas of good and bad, and think seriously about sociality and virtue.Envisioning nonhuman animals as distinct moral agents marks a paradigm shift in animal studies, as well as philosophy itself. Drawing not only on ethics and religion but also on law, sociology, and cognitive science, the essays in this collection test long-held certainties about moral boundaries and behaviors and prove that nonhuman animals possess complex reasoning capacities, sophisticated empathic sociality, and dynamic and enduring self-conceptions. Rather than claim animal morality is the same as human morality, this book builds an appreciation of the variety and character of animal sensitivities and perceptions across multiple disciplines, moving animal welfarism in promising new directions.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aAgent (Philosophy) 0aAgent (Philosophy). 0aAnimals (Philosophy) 0aAnimals (Philosophy). 0aConduct of life. 0aEthics. 7aNATURE / Animal Rights.2bisacsh1 aBathgate, Michael, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBekoff, Marc, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBerkman, John, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrane, Jonathan K., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCrane, Jonathan K., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDemetriou, Dan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoldfeder, Mark, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGross, Aaron S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHess, Kendy, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/re